Reasoning: The paper deals with the problem of universal decoding in the context of biometrical identification systems, where the decoder has access only to noisy versions of randomly generated codewords. The paper models the source, channel, and communication channel as non-unifilar, finite-state systems, which suggests that it belongs to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also deals with error probability and error exponent, which are common topics in the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. The paper proposes a metric based on Lempel-Ziv incremental parsing, which is a technique used in Machine Learning and Artificial Intelligence (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also deals with probability distributions and finite-state channels, which are topics in the Signal Processing (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the analysis of the effective induced channel, which suggests that it belongs to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category.
